18
00:01:06.381 --> 00:01:10.520
In fact, we're going to start by focusing
on a great visualization tool called

19
00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:12.540
conditional formatting.

20
00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:17.061
>> I understand conditional formatting
is where we change the formatting, say,

21
00:01:17.061 --> 00:01:20.651
color of a cell or cells where
it meets a particular condition.

22
00:01:20.651 --> 00:01:24.930
Can you give us some examples of why
we would use conditional formatting?

23
00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:28.680
>> Well,
it can be used to show trends in our data.

24
00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:32.592
We can identify anomalies like
duplicates or values that fall below or

25
00:01:32.592 --> 00:01:34.193
above a certain threshold.

26
00:01:34.193 --> 00:01:37.936
It can also be used interactively for
users to explore the data and

27
00:01:37.936 --> 00:01:41.067
highlight values that meet
their specific criteria.

28
00:01:41.067 --> 00:01:42.632
>> All sounding very useful.

29
00:01:42.632 --> 00:01:46.375
Please tell me more about how we
can achieve this interactivity.

30
00:01:46.375 --> 00:01:49.641
>> Well, there are a few
techniques we're going to explore.

31
