appears in the shape.

54
00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:15.196
>> The last topic we're going to cover
is quite unusual in this context,

55
00:03:15.196 --> 00:03:16.732
custom number formats.

56
00:03:16.732 --> 00:03:20.090
Can you please explain what these are?

57
00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:23.907
>> Well Excel allows us to specify
how we want our numbers to look.

58
00:03:23.907 --> 00:03:28.741
It provides us with built-in number
formats, like currency and percentage, but

59
00:03:28.741 --> 00:03:31.986
if we want something other
than the built-in options,

60
00:03:31.986 --> 00:03:34.623
we can create our own
custom number formats.

61
00:03:34.623 --> 00:03:38.586
This might be something as simple
as wanting all the zeros to appear

62
00:03:38.586 --> 00:03:42.430
as blank cells, or maybe even have
your dates show as just year.

63
00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:46.466
But we can get quite creative and
include colors and symbols, and it's

64
00:03:46.466 --> 00:03:50.985
a little bit like conditional formatting,
but actually, with more options.

65
00:03:50.985 --> 00:03:54.002
>> I think that's going to be
new to quite a lot of people.

